State management is one of the biggest challenges in growing Angular applications. As features multiply, components become overloaded with logic, services turn into god classes, race conditions appear, and debugging becomes a nightmare.
CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation) offers an elegant solution. It strictly separates operations that read data (Queries) from operations that write data (Commands). This separation leads to a more predictable state, better performance, easier testing, and clearer code.
Angular, especially when paired with NgRx, is a natural home for CQRS. In this article, we’ll explore how to implement it effectively with real-world examples, best practices, and practical guidance.

Why CQRS Matters in Frontend (and Why Angular Excels at It)
In traditional state management, the same service or store often handles both reading and mutating data. This leads to side effects hidden in unexpected places and makes reasoning about the application difficult.
CQRS brings clarity:

• Commands (write) → Intent to change something.

• Queries (read) → Ask for the current state without side effects.
NgRx implements CQRS principles natively:

• Actions = Commands

• Selectors = Queries

• Effects = Use cases/side effects

• Reducers = Pure state transitions
This alignment makes Angular one of the strongest frameworks for applying CQRS in the frontend.

