Commands vs Queries — Deep Dive with Real-World Example
Let’s use an E-commerce Shopping Cart as our running example.
1. Commands (Write Operations)
Commands express intent to change the system. They are simple, immutable objects.
// presentation/state/cart/cart.actions.ts
import { createAction, props } from '@ngrx/store';
export const addToCart = createAction(
'[Cart] Add Item',
props<{ productId: string; quantity: number }>()
);
export const removeFromCart = createAction(
'[Cart] Remove Item',
props<{ productId: string }>()
);
export const clearCart = createAction('[Cart] Clear Cart');
export const addToCartSuccess = createAction(
'[Cart] Add Item Success',
props<{ cart: Cart }>()
);
export const addToCartFailure = createAction(
'[Cart] Add Item Failure',
props<{ error: string }>()
);Dispatching from a Facade (recommended):
// presentation/state/cart/cart.facade.ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CartFacade {
constructor(private store: Store) {} addItem(productId: string, quantity: number): void {
this.store.dispatch(addToCart({ productId, quantity }));
}
removeItem(productId: string): void {
this.store.dispatch(removeFromCart({ productId }));
}
}

2. Queries (Read Operations)
Queries are pure functions that retrieve and transform state. They should be highly optimized and composable.
// presentation/state/cart/cart.selectors.ts
import { createFeatureSelector, createSelector } from '@ngrx/store';
import { CartState } from './cart.reducer';
import { CartItem } from '../../domain/entities/cart-item';export const selectCartState = createFeatureSelector<CartState>('cart');
export const selectCartItems = createSelector(
selectCartState,
(state) => state.items
);
export const selectCartTotalItems = createSelector(
selectCartItems,
(items) => items.reduce((total, item) => total + item.quantity, 0)
);
export const selectCartTotalPrice = createSelector(
selectCartItems,
(items) => items.reduce((total, item) => total + (item.price * item.quantity), 0)
);
export const selectIsCartEmpty = createSelector(
selectCartItems,
(items) => items.length === 0
);
Consuming in Components (clean & reactive):
@Component({
selector: 'app-cart-summary',
standalone: true,
template: `
<div *ngIf="cartItems$ | async as items">
<p>Total items: {{ totalItems$ | async }}</p>
<p>Total: {{ totalPrice$ | async | currency }}</p>
</div>
`
})
export class CartSummaryComponent {
cartItems$ = this.cartFacade.cartItems$;
totalItems$ = this.cartFacade.totalItems$;
totalPrice$ = this.cartFacade.totalPrice$;constructor(private cartFacade: CartFacade) {}
}

NgRx Effects — Where the Real Work Happens
Effects handle side effects and bridge commands with the Application / Infrastructure layers.
// presentation/state/cart/cart.effects.ts
@Injectable()
export class CartEffects {
addToCart$ = createEffect(() =>
this.actions$.pipe(
ofType(addToCart),
switchMap(({ productId, quantity }) =>
this.addToCartUseCase.execute(productId, quantity).pipe(
map(cart => addToCartSuccess({ cart })),
catchError(error => of(addToCartFailure({ error: error.message })))
)
)
)
); constructor(
private actions$: Actions,
private addToCartUseCase: AddToCartUseCase // from Application layer
) {}
}
This keeps your use cases clean and reusable across different state management solutions if needed.

Reducers — Pure State Transitions
// presentation/state/cart/cart.reducer.ts
export interface CartState extends EntityState<CartItem> {
totalPrice: number;
lastUpdated: Date;
}export const cartReducer = createReducer(
initialState,
on(addToCartSuccess, (state, { cart }) => ({
...state,
...cart,
lastUpdated: new Date()
})),
on(removeFromCart, (state, { productId }) => {
// pure transformation logic
})
);
Facades — The Component-Friendly API
Facades are one of the most important best practices when using NgRx + CQRS. They hide the complexity of the store from your components, making them cleaner, easier to test, and more maintainable.
// presentation/state/cart/cart.facade.ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CartFacade {
// Queries (Observables)
cartItems$ = this.store.select(selectCartItems);
totalPrice$ = this.store.select(selectCartTotalPrice);
itemCount$ = this.store.select(selectCartItemCount);
isEmpty$ = this.store.select(selectIsCartEmpty);
loading$ = this.store.select(selectCartLoading);
error$ = this.store.select(selectCartError); constructor(private store: Store<AppState>) {}
// Commands
addItem(productId: string, quantity: number): void {
this.store.dispatch(addToCart({ productId, quantity }));
}
removeItem(productId: string): void {
this.store.dispatch(removeFromCart({ productId }));
}
clearCart(): void {
this.store.dispatch(clearCart());
}
// Optional: Command that returns an observable for components that need to react
addItemAndGetResult(productId: string, quantity: number): Observable<Cart> {
this.store.dispatch(addToCart({ productId, quantity }));
return this.actions$.pipe(
ofType(addToCartSuccess),
filter(action => /* optional filter logic */ true),
take(1)
);
}
}
Usage in Component (very clean):
@Component({
selector: 'app-cart',
standalone: true,
template: `
<div *ngIf="cartItems$ | async as items">
<app-cart-item
*ngFor="let item of items"
[item]="item"
(remove)="facade.removeItem($event)">
</app-cart-item><p>Total: {{ totalPrice$ | async | currency }}</p>
<button (click)="facade.clearCart()">Clear Cart</button>
</div>
`
})
export class CartComponent {
cartItems$ = this.facade.cartItems$;
totalPrice$ = this.facade.totalPrice$;
constructor(public facade: CartFacade) {} // Public for template access
}
Benefits of Facades:

• Components stay dumb and focused on UI

• Easier unit testing (mock the facade instead of the whole store)

• Single source of truth for feature state API

• Smoother refactoring if you ever change state management

When to Use Full NgRx + CQRS vs Lighter Solutions
Use Full NgRx CQRS when:

• Large enterprise application with many developers

• Complex global state and cross-feature interactions

• Need for time-travel debugging, DevTools, or undo/redo

• High requirements for predictability and auditability
Consider lighter alternatives when:

• Small to medium apps → Use Signals (Angular 17+) or signalStore

• Feature-local state → NgRx ComponentStore or plain BehaviorSubject services

• Simple forms and local UI state → Reactive Forms + Signals
Modern Angular gives you a full spectrum of solutions.

Conclusion
CQRS, when implemented with NgRx in Angular, brings predictability, testability, and scalability to your state management. By clearly separating Commands (Actions) from Queries (Selectors), and isolating side effects in Effects, you create a system that is much easier to understand and evolve.
Combined with Clean Architecture (from the previous article), your Angular application becomes a truly enterprise-grade frontend.
